If 2022 was a hard year, you’re not alone 🤍

Mentally, this was one of my toughest years so far. After 2 years of caring for two sets of twins 24/7 in a pandemic, I reached my breaking point. I was not in a good place. Thank God for Michael because he urged me to get help, pleaded with me to agree to sending the kids to public school, & to start therapy again. Most people probably would’ve never known what was happening inside my head because I was really good at putting on a smile. But things were far from okay.

I’m sharing this because I know it’s been a hard year for so many people and oftentimes you don’t even know someone is breaking. They may seem happy, they may be smiling for the pictures, they may be doing all the things…but when no one’s around, they’re really hurting.

So check on your loved ones. Never be afraid to call someone out. Ask the hard questions. Call #988. It could change everything 🤍

Just feeling really grateful today. We were walking around our neighborhood tonight, me walking Chloe on her leash, Michael pushing the little girls in the stroller, and the big riding their bikes and hit me. This is what I prayed so hard for. For years, Michael and I would walk Chloe and dream of the day we’d have little ones with us. And now we have four. ✨😭 

God is good. He is faithful. The wait is SO worth it, friend💕

I had severe, crippling anxiety at night that made it difficult to sleep and I really couldn’t understand what God was doing. & yet He carried me through that season & so many since then.

Worrying about the future only robs us of today. So the best thing we can do is trust in the One who goes before us. He has a plan. & it’s always far better than anything we could’ve dreamed up on our own 💕

My Dad met Jesus last Thursday. & while I’m still in shock that this is happening, I’ll cling to these memories. Because there are oh so many good ones. Love you forever Dad. See you soon 💕

Thankful for that last day together 💔

Y’all, my dad was a pretty healthy guy. He had a physical the week beforehand and everything looked fine. He loved to hike and stay active. Yet, his heart stopped on a hike in California. He was only 63. We all thought we had a lot more time. 

So tell your loved ones how much they mean to you, hug them, take all the videos and pictures. You just never know when it’ll be the last time 💔

Our biggest adventure yet 🙃🇳🇱 

Trusting in God’s plan & following His lead…

Holland, here we come!! 💕🌷🚲

Why? When? How? 👇🏼

God planted a seed in hearts last summer of living abroad with our kids. We felt this tug to go somewhere simpler, more family-focused. We knew Michael had job opportunities in Amsterdam because we first looked into this after we lost Noah almost 10 years ago. The timing just wasn’t right then as our focus was battling infertility & having a family. 

When we went to the Netherlands last August, we didn’t want to leave. The public transportation, the culture, the history, the work-life balance, & the general desire to do everything slower & simpler really made us start to wonder if we should do it. We knew if we waited much longer, learning the language & settling in would be much more difficult for the kids. 

We currently plan to be there for 2 years. The kids will go to school there so they can make friends easier & learn Dutch! We are selling our home & most of our possessions (including cars!) because it’s easier to get things there than ship them from here. We are tentatively moving late April. We will bike everywhere & use the trains & get to travel all over Europe with our kids. 🌎 

We’ve met many expat families along the way & are excited for the adventure. This is something we’ve been seriously praying about for 8 months & God really opened a lot of doors to make this happen. & if it wasn’t obvious, we’re absolutely terrified but we’re going for it anyways 🙃

Dad, I thought we had a lot more time. I know you never expected to go this early but I’m thankful for the One who did. This was no surprise to Him. And while our hearts are broken & this all still feels like a nightmare, knowing you’re in Heaven with my boys and your dad and Mom’s parents and sooo many others….gives me comfort ❤️ You once told me you had a dream where you saw Noah & Grandpa walking hand in hand in Heaven. & Now I get to picture the 3 of y’all together, swinging Noah in the middle. 3 generations in Heaven together. I’ll love you always. I hope we make you proud down here. I’ll see you soon ❤️

My dad was buried next to our Noah this morning. Never thought I’d be burying my dad less than 10 years after burying Noah. But I know God did. The fact that this plot was available was a God wink. I just know they’re together 💙💙

Her little voice singing “Holy is the Lord” 😭💕

“I have no greater joy than to hear that my children are walking in the truth.“ 3 John 4 ❤️

In my feels as I have to prepare to say “see ya later” to my ride or die of almost a decade. From weddings, infertility, motherhood, child loss and the day to day, our friendship has been a constant. No matter what. And now there will be oceans between us. 💔 No dinner dates or weekends away, no constant communications (stupid time differences) and no play dates with the kids. I know it won’t change a thing. Oceans can’t come between the friendship we’ve built. Love you forever.

& now to make so many memories in Europe ✈️ 🌎 

Society tells us the fun ends when we have kids. That we can no long travel & go on adventures. Well, even with 2 sets of twins, we’re doing it 😉 It definitely comes with its challenges, but I look back on all our adventures & I’m thankful we did it anyways!🙃

✨Do the family photos✨

I’m so thankful for the family photos I have of my whole family & I treasure them even more now that my Dad is gone. While we were in Broken Bow, I decided we needed to get our photos done with Michael’s side of the family since it had been far too many years. And I’m so thankful we did.

Are pictures stressful? Yes. 
Is it a lot of money? Yes. 
But I never ever regret doing it. 
Especially after losing loved ones unexpectedly, the photos we have of them are worth more than gold 💕

So whether you prop your phone and do a family selfie, or schedule professional photos, take the pictures, friends. 📸

7 years in a blink 🥹✨

Tulips have always been my favorite flower so Michael’s been getting me tulips for 16 years. The year L&M we’re born, a family moved here from the Netherlands & started @texas.tulips & now we have the cutest little tulip farm just 20 minutes from our house. We had to go one last time before we move to the Netherlands in April 🌷💕 It’s just wild to see all these little points connecting, leading us to this big move! 🇳🇱 🚲

We’re definitely terrified, but we’re doing it anyways ❤️

Michael & I were both saying just last night how nuts we feel for doing this. For selling everything we own & leaving everything we know to move to another continent. With 4 kids…🫠. To be honest, selling our house & booking those one-way flights to Amsterdam made it pretty dang real 🙈. While we KNOW this is what God has planned for us, we’re still terrified to actually be doing it. We know He’s gone before us, opening so many doors that never should’ve been opened, so we’re trusting that He’s got us. We have less than 6 weeks left in the US & I kinda want to puke writing that 🙃

So if you have any extra prayers, I’d love some sent our way. For Michael & I, and for the kids, and for all the people were going to miss like crazy ❤️

Reading “Fox in Socks” to her twin 🥹💕

These two loveeeeee reading & it’s so cute to hear them “read” to each other 💕

Also, how cute is it going to be when they start speaking Dutch? 😂😍🇳🇱

Just a few of the many reasons 💕

I don’t know if #mancrushmonday is still a thing but I’m just feeling really thankful for this guy today. He’s been the biggest part of my life for over half of it & I’m really freaking thankful 💕✨

Also, we both went to high school with @troycartwright who sings this song 👏🏼

Trading it all in to live MORE with LESS 💕

T-28 days until we leave everything & everyone we know to move to The Netherlands 🤯 We’ve lived in our current home for over 5 years and it’s truly mind-blowing how much crap we’ve accumulated 🙈 It actually feels really good to purge, donate, sell so much!

Last week, I was terrified. This week, I’m excited for this new adventure. I’m sure I’ll keep flipping back and forth between now and moving day 🙃

I’m going to start sharing more clips from the last few months, looking for housing, applying for visas, learning Dutch, etc! Let me know what you want to hear more about 💕👇🏼

“If God meant for us to stay in one place, He would’ve given us roots as opposed to feet.” 

That was written in my devotional almost 9 months ago when we first started praying about moving to another country. There have been sooo many little God winks along the way, assuring us that this bold move is part of His plan. 🌍

As I decide what to take and what to donate, I’ll definitely be taking these @vivaia_official sustainable shoes. My life is about to consist of a lot of walking & biking so comfortable shoes is a MUST! I love that these are made from a variety of eco-friendly materials including recycled plastic water bottles. So cool! 🤯🙌🏼 They’re also super breathable & padded & the best part? Machine washable! They gave me code VIVAIAJ10 to share with y’all to save 10%! 👟

#vivaia #vpurpose  #vivaiaonmyway

What we’re bringing with us! 📦🌍

Housing in the Netherlands is quite small (🙈) compared to what we’re used to here so if it’s not super important, we’re not bringing it. We are shipping a handful of things like my dad’s desk (it’s been in the family for 4 generations), Michael’s computers, photo books, & the kids’ favorite toys. Then we’re stuffing our clothes & shoes in as many suitcases as we can handle & getting any other necessities there. I’m sure we’ll be buying out the IKEA once we get there 🙃😂

I’ve been channeling @mariekondo as I go through our things and decide what we want to bring vs what should be donated/sold/trashed & it actually feels really good to get rid of things! 👏🏼

T-26 days! 🙃

@chatbooks 20% off code: JENNDARBY

We have a home in the Netherlands! 🎉💕

The housing market in the Netherlands (even just to rent!) is crazy! So when we were out-bid on other homes, we started getting really nervous about not having a place to live. We found this place yesterday, our realtor sent us some videos of the inside, and we made an offer! We knew there was a chance they could get other offers but when the owners asked if we could meet over Zoom, I was feeling optimistic that maybe they’d choose us! The owners are SO sweet & immediately offered us their home 🥹

There were so many little things that made this home perfect for us & I just know it was a whole lot of Jesus & some extra luck from my dad on his birthday 💕🍀 

We can’t wait to make so many memories abroad!
😍🌍🚲🌷🇳🇱

A little reminder for your heart ❤️

I should probably be freaking out a lot more than I am over the fact that we’re moving to another country in a few weeks. But “I have peace that makes no sense.” Because I know God has been orchestrating this move for a long time.

I know he kept us here longer than we expected because He wanted us to have more time with my dad before he died. And so our house would sell in a better market. And so my friends & family had more time to adjust to the idea. And so there was room at the kids’ new school despite a waitlist. And so many other reasons.

I could write a book on all the ways God has showed up for us over the last 11 years of marriage. If you’re in a season of waiting for God to show up, it probably won’t happen in your timing, but He will. Because He protects us from our own desires to give us immeasurably more than we could ever ask or imagine.❤️✨

…and lose our free babysitting 😭💔😂

So glad Michael booked this little staycation for us. We’ve been doing alllllll the things to prep for this international move & it was so nice to get away for 48 hours without the kids! We rested, ate warm meals together, picked out all our furniture for our new place at IKEA, and saw one last movie together🍿

Date nights will be hard to come by once we move to the Netherlands so I’m thankful for this time away 💕

Suitcases are from @nomatic & they also made the backpacks we used when we went to Europe last summer! They have the bestttt travel gear, trust me! 💕

that last one has been the hardest 🫠📦 

T- 12 days until we move our family of 6 plus a dog across the world 🌍 To be honest, there’s a lotttttt to do pack/sell/donate. But I’m a procrastinator & work best under pressure so we’ll get there 😂🙌🏼

If you’re local & want any home decor/kitchen items, let me know 🙃

Another bucket list item ✔️🥹

My friend & I decided to surprise our kids with 24 hours at Great Wolf Lodge as one final sleepover/hangout before we move to Amsterdam next week. To say they were surprised & ecstatic would be an understatement 🥹💕

The twins have been best friends with my best friends’ kids since they were barely a year old. They’ve seen each other through losing siblings and moving and pandemics and homeschooling. I’m so thankful for their bond & they’re going to miss them like crazy.

This is the hardest part of saying yes to what we know is God’s plan. Saying “see you later!” to the people we love most. 💔 But we know it’s not goodbye forever, just goodbye for now 💕

Another bucket list item checked off before moving continents 🙃🌍 

My dad *always* signed my birthday cards & anniversary cards with “DAD 🙂” so it felt fitting to get his handwriting tattooed on my arm so I can have him with me wherever I go 💕

Thankful for friends who are always down for another tattoo 👯‍♀️ This was our second tattoo together & I don’t think it’ll be our last 🙈

✨This night is sparkling, don’t you let it go✨

Michael surprised us with Taylor Swift tickets & WOW she never disappoints!! 3 hours of all our favorite songs & the besttttt show!! Who was there?! She’s superhuman 🦸🏼‍♀️

3 years sure went fast 😭💕

My double rainbow babies came exactly when God knew we’d need them. They’ve kept us laughing through pandemics, homeschooling, and now days away from moving to Europe. These two brighten up all our days and I’m forever grateful God chose me to be their mama 💕

Yep, I’m panicking 🫠

It’s so strange to be 3 days out from something we’ve been talking about daily for 9 months. Selling/donating everything you own is A LOT. Packing 6 people and a dog to fly across the world is A LOT. Saying “see you later” to everyone we love is hard.💔

We so appreciate your prayers over the next few days as we take this big leap ✈️💕🇳🇱

The things you find while packing your life up 🥹💕

This was our wedding invitation 11 years ago! I remember thinking time was moving sooo slowly while we were engaged. Now suddenly I’ve blinked & those two kids getting married are now moving to another continent with their 4 kids. Ain’t it funny how life changes? 💕

We made it to Holland! 🌷🎉

The past 3 days have been a whirlwind & I’m pretty sure we’ve felt every emotion but we did the dang thing, y’all. We packed up our life & moved to another continent. I wish I could share all ways God has shown up for us over the past few days because it’s truly brought so much peace to my anxious heart. Anyone who knows me knows this is VERY outside my comfort zone. Never in a million years did I think we’d be doing this. With 4 kids. But God 💕

I can’t wait to share more about our travels and the first 24 hours in our new home. Our furniture comes tomorrow and then I’ll do a little house tour! For now, can you guess how many times we’ve fallen down these crazy narrow Netherlands stairs? 🫠😂🙈

Feeling more Dutch already 😉🚲🎉

Wait til y’all see me cruising in my bakfiets with the twins 😂🚲 Think minivan but bike version 🙃 It’s basically a bike with a huge bucket on the front for kid to ride in! I really was just proud that I didn’t wreck it on our bike ride home 😂🙌🏼 If you see someone struggling on a bakfiets around Amsterdam, it’s probably me 🙈

Today was probably our hardest day yet 🫠 Lots of tears, crying, tantrums, frustration, anxiety, etc.

We knew moving to another country with 4 kids wouldn’t be simple but today I was ready to fly home to what’s comfortable & normal. 🙈

But seeing how much M&L have adapted already makes me smile. They’re already thriving here. They love biking everywhere, they love the independence they get from living in a safer place, & they’ve made quite a few Dutch friends already. Big prayers answered by God.

So while I know there will be many more hard days, I’m choosing to focus on the fact that God lead us here for a purpose & there’s so much joy to be found in this new adventure 💕

My 2 twin B’s are loving this Amsterdam weather ⛅️

Highlights from the past few days:
•Maddie & Liam LOVED their first two days at Dutch school!
•We figured out the bus system 😂🙌🏼
•M&L play outside with their neighborhood friends every single day and it makes my heart burst 💕
•We officially finished building 4 bunk beds, our bed, 1 guest bed, 1 sofa, 1 loveseat, 1 dining table, 6 chairs, 4 barstools, 1 office desk, and probably a few other things I’m missing 🫠 I don’t ever want to build another thing from IKEA 😂
•Chloe is finally going up AND down these crazy Netherlands stairs 🙌🏼🐶
•laundry is going to be 80% of my life given the size of the washer/dryers here & the fact that our laundry room is on our third floor 🙈
•seeing my kids adapt to a new country, a new culture, a new language makes me the proudest mom 🥰

Is there anything more Holland than tulips?! 🌷💕

It’s peak blooming season @visitkeukenhof so of course we had to spend our first weekend here seeing all the flowers!! The weather was perfect & we even met up with a fellow expat & photographer @stephanierossphotography to get our first family photos on the Netherlands 🇳🇱💕 Each day, we feel a little more settled so thank you for your prayers! We feel them! 🥹

Netherlands friends- where should we go next?! 📍

Week one of living in Europe with 4 kids ✔️🇳🇱

We’ve had some very high highs and some very low lows over the last 7 days but that’s to be expected when you sell everything, leave everything and everyone you know, and move to another continent with 4 kids. We’re slowly settling into our new home and getting to know our way around our neighborhood. We’re keeping Amazon & IKEA in business 🙃😂 and we’re definitely working off all the pastries we’re eating with all the activity 🙌🏼

It honestly doesn’t feel real yet. Still feels like we’re on a weird vacation somewhere 😂 But I think it’ll hit within the next few weeks that we legit moved here 🫠💕

I’m trying to share the good and the bad because I know this is something so many people consider doing. It definitely hasn’t been all rainbows & sunshine but I know in time & as we find a routine, we will all adjust to this new life!💕

Hoping to share a house tour this week! It’s taken a bit to get everything built amongst the immigration appointments, 4 children, jet lag, etc 😂

Never thought I’d be living in Europe on my 33rd birthday 🙃

If you told me on my 32nd birthday what the following year would bring, I would’ve told you you were crazy 🤯 But life is kind of wild like that. You never know what lies ahead so do what you feel God’s calling you to do, no matter how crazy it feels 💕

Thank you for all the birthday wishes today! It was a beautiful day spent with my little loves in The Netherlands 🇳🇱🌷🚲

Liv thought she was getting free money 😉💶

Grocery shopping in Europe?
🛒 make sure you have a euro for a grocery cart! If you return the cart, you’ll get your euro back 😉
🛒bring your own bags!! or else you’ll be buying lots of reusable bags 😂🙋🏼‍♀️
🛒Google lens lets you hold your phone camera up to anything and translate the label!🙌🏼
🛒while most places in Europe don’t have free public bathrooms, most grocery stores will let you in the back if you show you have a toddler needing the potty 🫠
🛒keep your receipt handy because you’ll likely need to scan it to leave the store 🙃
🛒get ready to go grocery shopping nearly everyday because of how small the refrigerators are 🙈

Biking to the grocery store is quickly becoming a nightly event 🚲😂

Real life house tour of an expat family of 6! 🏠🇳🇱 

Housing in the Netherlands is WILD. There’s a shortage so even just to rent a home, you have to bid! We put (*over ask*) offers on 2 other homes before getting this one. This home is over 110 years old, 3 stories, and has SO much character. I’ll share more of the details soon 🥹

We brought almost nothing with us so everything had to be bought and assembled by us once we got here 🙃 Y’all wanted to see what our new place looks like, moving mess & all, so here it is! 😂🙌🏼 For being here less than 2 weeks and have 4 kids too, I’d say we’re getting there! 📦

I’ve had soooo many ask how *exactly* we got here 🇳🇱👇🏼

A few years ago, we started feeling like God wanted us to make a big move. Last summer, it felt like everything was pointing to Europe which felt crazy because I’m a homebody & we have 4 kids & all our family lived within 20 mins of us. But we couldn’t shake the feeling that God wanted us elsewhere.

Michael started asking around at work, knowing they had European offices. One position had been available for months that they hadn’t been able to fill. The job was almost exactly what Michael has been doing for years, except for on the European team instead of the US. I prayed for months that if God didn’t want us there, He’d slam the doors shut. Instead, every door that felt impossible kept opening. He interviewed & accepted the position for the European team which is how we were able to get our visas.

Before he got that job, we also started researching DAFT visas (Dutch American Friendship Treaty). Basically you can apply for a visa here by showing you’re running your own business. I love all these traditions!! In Texas, high schoolers have exams but just based on that year & they have to pass with their overall grades. Once they’ve passed, their parents hang their bags on the flagpole! Then they have smaller, cozier ceremonies with just a handful of students. They gather around  tables & sign their diplomas together (no walking across the stage to receive it!). And apparently only the students that graduate with distinction wear caps. 🎉

Let’s add a broken bone to this adventure 🙃🩹

Around 5am I heard a thud from the girls room next to us and then crying. I went in to find Emmy had fallen off her bed while sleeping (not a bunk bed—a little ikea bed like a meter off the ground). She’s normally easily to console but she wouldn’t stop saying her shoulder hurt. She didn’t want to suck her thumb from that side and and wouldn’t move her arm up very high. My mom gut told me something was broken.

I called the urgent line at our GP and they sent word to the hospital that we’d be coming. I then called my sweet neighbor @yallingupdesigns because I saw it was still dark outside and cold and raining and new taking her by myself in the bakfiets wasn’t going to work. Thankfully she drove us to the hospital AND stayed with us to help with translating.😭👏🏼

We saw two nurses at first who both thought she was fine but they said they would have the hospital GP look at it. The GP came in and said she wanted the surgeon (I think they meant specialist? Like an ortho doc? But they kept saying surgeon) to see it. That doctor came in and immediately ordered an X-ray. 🩻 

I took her to the X-ray and had to hold her in place while they took the images which was heart wrenching 💔 Shortly after, the specialist came back in and confirmed she’d broken her clavicle 💔. You obviously can’t put a cast on a clavicle so she gets to wear a sling for a week or two while her bone heals.

Poor Emmy was such a trooper and I’m really thankful for our Tylenol & Motrin stockpile we brought with us from the US 😂👏🏼 Also, I was so impressed with the hospital and staff and we were in and out in an hour. (That would never happen in the US). Hopefully she’s back to her wild self in no time!

Just a little bit different than in the states 🙃😂

After 3 days of high fevers, no appetite, vomiting & fatigue, the nurse in me decided it was time to have her seen. Here in the Netherlands, everyone sees a GP (vs having the kids see the pediatrician) and most people don’t go to the doctor unless they’re very very ill. They live by “tea & rest”. Which definitely helps for wait times!

They got us in within 30 mins of me calling and we waited in the waiting room for maybe 10 minutes. In the states, a nurse or medical assistant typically brings you back for vital signs before you see the doctor but none of that happens here. The doctor comes and gets you from the waiting room (can y’all ever imagine this happening in the states?😂) & takes you back to their office/exam room (it’s in the same room). The doctor swabbed her throat but there’s no rapid tests here apparently so they have to send it off to a lab & we won’t know the results until next week 🙈.

She did, however, prescribe me an antibiotic to start this weekend if things don’t get any better (really appreciated that!). We were in & out in 20 minutes and it’s still SO strange not having to pay 😂👏🏼 

Overall, it feels more efficient & natural which is kind of nice! So far,  no complaints on the health care here!🙌🏼

Recipe for Rice Crispie Treats 👇🏼

You’ll need a box of Rice Crispies, a bag of marshmallows & 3 tbsp of butter!

1. Heat the marshmallows and butter on the stove on medium heat until fully melted (keep mixing, it happens faster than you think!)
2. Pour Rice Crispies into melted marshmallow mixture. I did a little at a time to mix it well and get the right consistency. I ended up using 3/4 of the box.
3. Scoop into a 9x13 pan and when cool enough, pat down with your hands (add butter or oil to your hands so the rice crispies don’t stick to you!)
4. Enjoy!! 🤤😍

Let’s talk about anxiety & grief 💔

When you lose someone you love, it’s hard not to let grief invade every aspect of your life. The “what if’s” can so easily consume us. I guess the enemy knows that’s when it’s the best time to attack.

Over the last decade, we’ve had quite a few seasons of immense grief. Losing our first son to preterm labor, suffering miscarriages, losing my dad so suddenly. And it’s always when I’m grieving a big loss, that anxiety overtakes everything else.

For months, I’ve feared something happening to Michael. Every time he’s not feeling well, has a migraine, etc, my mind immediately jumps to worst case scenario. It’s hard not to “go there” after the last year of our lives. And the train doesn’t stop there. It keeps going if I let it. To what would happen to the kids & I and where would we go and before you know it, you’ve spent 20 minutes thinking about some made-up awful scenario that will most likely never happen. 

It’s easier said than done, but I know my God doesn’t want me to live in fear. Because none of us are guaranteed tomorrow & worrying only robs us of today.

Psalm 46:10 “Be still & know that I am God.” 
God’s bigger than any fear we could ever have. 🩷

Sinterklaas is coming this weekend! 🇳🇱

I’ve had to quite a few of my US friends ask what the difference is between Sinterklaas and Santa Clause. I think Santa Clause actually originated from Sinterklaas and Americans just started combining it with Christmas. But here it’s a totally separate thing from Christmas. 

Sinterklaas comes on a steamboat from Spain with his white horse his Pieten (his helpers!) Every night between November 18 and December 5, kids leave their shoes out by the fireplace or front door so that Sinterklaas and his pieten can leave a treat in them. Normally it’s chocolate, a little gift, some Kruidnoten, etc. Then on the eve of Sinterklaas’ birthday, he leaves a bag of bigger presents on your doorstep.

Just like with Santa Clause, it seems there are different ways to celebrate this but overall this is commonly what I’m hearing! 

We obviously still will be celebrating Christmas as the birth of our Savior but it’s fun to join in on these Dutch traditions too! 🩷
